EXAMINING RED WINE QUALITY by RAGHAV BATRA

Data courtesy of:

P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553. ISSN: 0167-9236.

This data set contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

This is an initial description of the data:

# new variable: definition of free SO2 percent
redWine$freeSO2percent = redWine$free.sulfur.dioxide/redWine$total.sulfur.dioxide

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

This dataset consists of ~ 1600 rows of observations on red wine over 12 key indicators (fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid levels, residual sugar, chlorides, free SO2, total SO2, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol content, quality).

Some other facts: 1. All the wines are mildy acidic, with pH levels between 3 and 4, the mean being 3.3 2. Most of the wines are rated as mediocre in quality, with the mean as 5.6 and median as 6. 3. The resiudal sugar content peaks at 4, and has a long tail. 4. Wines with excess levels of sugars have a mediocre quality. 5. Approximately 33.3% of wines have excess free SO2 levels. Such kinds of wine have a larger spread in quality, but the average wine is such a category is still mediocre 6. There is a spike in the number of wines with exactly 50% free SO2 concentration 7. There are fewer and more dispersed chloride levels with high values 8. Volatile acidity is concentrated within a range of 0.3 and 0.8, with 80% of wines with such levels. 9. Most wines have little citric acid content. There is a spike at 0.5. 10. Alcohol percent level maxes at 9.5.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Quality is the main variable I want to predict. I do not currently know which variable has the highest contribution to this variable, but excess levels of substances such as SO2 and sugar do detract from the quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

As said above, I feel moderate levels of helpful substances and above moderate levels of substances that create smell and taste will help predict good quality wines. As such, this can be tested better in the bivariate analysis.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes. 1. freeSO2evident is a logical categorical variable that measures if the total SO2 in the wine is evident (> 50 ppm). 2. freeSO2percent is a ratio of the free SO2 to the total SO2.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

  1. Residual sugars and alcohol had long tails, which I fixed using a log transformation.
  2. Chlorides had a lot of small outlier data, which I fixed by narrowing the limits of observation.
  3. FreeSO2percent had a spike at 50%, but that might as well be accurate data.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

From the obvious scatterplots and correlation tests, it seems that alcohol quality is heavily correlated with:

  1. higher alcohol percent (positive).
  2. lower volatile acidity (negative).

While these 2 had the highest correlation for quality, other variables also seemed to affect wine quality:

  1. Citric acid had a weak positive relationship.
  2. Lower and middle values of residual sugar promise to give . rise to higher quality wines.
  3. Lower levels of chloride have more change of producing a better quality wine.
  4. High quality wines have sulphate levels less than 1.
  5. Free SO2 percent levels seem to have no effect on wine quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

  1. Fixed acidity (tartaric acid) and citric acid have a highly positive relation.
  2. Volatile acidity (acetic acid) and citric acid have a mediocrely negative relation.

As quality and citric acid levels are positively correlated, this implies better quality red wines have higher tartaric acid and lower acetic acid content.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

Between fixed acidity and citric acid: 0.67

Modelling the dataset

Let’s model the data to predict quality!

redWine_cleaned = subset(redWine, (redWine$chlorides <= 0.11 & redWine$chlorides >= 0.03) 
                         & redWine$sulphates <= 1.0
                         & (redWine$residual.sugar >= 2 & redWine$residual.sugar <= 6)
                         & redWine$citric.acid <= 0.7)

redWine_cleaned$id = redWine_cleaned$X

m1 <- lm(quality ~ alcohol, data = redWine_cleaned)

m2 <- update(m1, ~ . + volatile.acidity)
m3 <- update(m2, ~ . + sulphates)
m4 <- update(m3, ~ . + chlorides)
m5 <- update(m4, ~ . + residual.sugar)
m6 <- update(m5, ~ . + citric.acid)

mtable(m1, m2, m3, m4, m5, m6)

Plot One

Description One

This plot displays the histogram of wines by citric acid content.

Though it might not have been very useful in determining the final quality, this graph has 2 interesting features:

  2. the spike at 0.5

While these may have been numerical errors, some research on my side told me that red wines generally have very little citric content.

Regarding the spike at 0.5, on further examination, all wines with such levels seemed to fit in with the data.

Thus, it turns out that both spikes were in fact alright! This is why I liked this graph: it gave me opportunities to both do some research and perform further analyses on what I thought was wrong. This is the whole point of this course!

Thus, while displaying counts, this graph also presents some interesting findings.

Description Two

This is a scatterplot of chloride content by quality.

While most people would not choose this graph for their final visualization because it’s too squishy, I actually like it because it achieves what I want from it very well.

Reflection

Phew! This was an interesting assignment. I found the layout of analyses to perform in the skeleton Markdown file very easy to follow. The fact I could perform so many analyses so easily was much appreciated!

In the end I discovered that red wine quality is dependent on alcohol content and volatile acidity (tartaric acid). It is also minorly dependent on sulphates, chlorides and residual sugar to a certain extent provided these values are below certain threshholds.

The main struggle with me were the new commands. I had to stop my train of thought, Google the queries and then try again if it didn’t work. However, tough as that may have been, I was happy I did so because there is no other way to this kind of learning!

Generally though, everything else went well. I would have liked more categorical variables. This is not to say I couldn’t create some (I did create one!); it’s just that they wouldn’t have given me any more information.

I genuinely learnt a lot about red wines and various chemicals.

Future insight could include comparing these results to results for some other type of alcohol such as gin or whiskey.

It would also be interesting to do a time series analysis of the chemicals and quality of the wine as it aged.
